>>62442241
Why not? World building is fun, and a good setting can be just as enjoyable to read about as a good character.
It can be anything, really. A space story could have a huge fleshed out universe, or you could simply focus on one little space station, while autistically detailing it's workings.
A medieval story could have a rich history, involving fallen empires, unique kingdoms, and fantastical mythology, or it could focus on the small adventures of a town worker dealing with uppity locals and unusual travelers.
Hell, you could just do what I did, and take a few nifty concepts, like SCP and Stargate, and just mash it into the modern world. Even with something like that, there's a lot of possibilities. A story of a regular guy being a fish out of water when he discovers the alien shit, or perhaps a sci Fi war story, or team of elites going off to avert some world ending disaster.

A unique setting opens up so many story possibilities, you'd be a fool to limit yourself to a pre-established universe unless you were a super fan of it's world.
